bib.title: Nuclear excitation functions from 40 to 200 MeV proton irradiation of terbium

free_txt: Thin terbium targets were irradiated
in the production target station of the Isotope
Production Facility at LANSCE and in the Target 2
Blue Room of the Weapons Neutron Research Facility.
Compiled by S.H.
Beam energy at each foil in the stack was calculated
using three different methods - MCNP6 simulations, the
SRIM/TRIM nuclear code, and an in-house developed tool.
The activity at the end of bombardment of each isotope
of interest was determined by fitting its decay curve.
Uncertainties in fitted parameters were computed from
covariance matrices as the standard deviation in
the activity extrapolated to the end of irradiation.
p-type aluminum windowed ORTEC GEM detector
with a relative efficiency of about 10% and
resolution of 1.99 keV at 1333 keV.
Total uncertainty obtained according to the
error propagation variance formula with estimated
contributing uncertainties from
combined uncertainties from detector
calibration and geometry reproducibility
syst. uncertainty in target foil dimensions
syst. uncertainty in proton flux
Multiple photopeaks were used when possible and
additional uncertainty as the standard deviation of
these complimentary measurements was combined with
the uncertainties described above
Thin terbium targets were irradiated
in the production target station of the Isotope
Production Facility at LANSCE and in the Target 2
Blue Room of the Weapons Neutron Research Facility.
Thin discs of natural terbium with purity of 99.9%
and nominal thickness 90 mg/cm2 in a stack with
aluminum plates and thin Al foils with purity of
99.999% and thickness of 20-50 mg/cm. Aluminum plates
were used to degrade the energy of the incident beam
to allow well-spaced measurements down to
approximately one half the beam's incident energy
Thin aluminum foils were used for monitor purposes.
